Boil a large #pot of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the potatoes. Wash the @new potatoes{700} (but keep the nutritious skins on). Cut the potatoes into quarters. Cook in the boiling water for ~{10-15%minutes} until cooked through.

Place your hand flat on each @pork medallion{1} and slice in half from the side. Lay the pork slices between 2 sheets of #clingfilm. Whack the pork, using the base of a pan or a #rolling pin, until it is 1cm thick.

Put the @panko breadcrumbs{2} in a big #bowl with @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good few grinds of @black pepper{a few grinds}. Coat each pork fillet evenly in a tbsp of @sour cream{4}. Press each fillet into the breadcrumbs until completely coated.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large #frying pan{}. Lay the pork schnitzels in the pan and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side.

> Cook these in batches to make sure the pan retains its heat and gives a lovely golden colour to the schnitzels. We cooked the pork until it was ever so slightly pink in the middle.

Drain your potatoes when they're done and rinse them under cold water for a minute. This will stop them from cooking further and cool them slightly for your lukewarm salad.

In a #bowl, use a #fork to whisk together the @Dijon mustard{1}, @balsamic vinegar{1} and @olive oil{1 1/2%tbsp} with a small pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}.

Toss the @wild rocket{4} and slightly cooled potatoes with this vinaigrette. Scatter the @Lilliput capers{2} on top.

> If the little ones don't like capers, you can just leave them out!

> To sweeten the vinaigrette, you can add a pinch of sugar.

Serve the schnitzels on the new potato salad and sprinkle over some @lemon{1}(zested).